                <fr:title text="inverses and invertibility in deductive systems">inverses and invertibility in deductive systems</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Inverses to morphisms in a <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-0048.xml" title="deductive system" addr="jms-0048" type="local">deductive system</fr:link> need not be unique due to the general failure of associativity; therefore, we must be careful when speaking of “invertible maps” or “isomorphisms”. It happens that both linear and thunkable inverses <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-004N.xml" title="linear and thunkable inverses" addr="jms-004N" type="local">are unique</fr:link>.</html:p>
                <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:authors>
                      <fr:author>
                        <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
